This paper deals with semantic analysis of text, which is a common topic in natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also employs unsupervised learning, which is a common technique in machine learning (ML) and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The paper also involves mining for associations between concepts, which is a common task in information retrieval (IR), making cs.IR a likely sub-category. The paper also evaluates the performance of the proposed method using benchmark datasets, which is a common practice in machine learning and data mining (DM), making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of encyclopedic corpora, which is a common source of data in deep learning (DL), making cs.DL (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category.
